observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management 
12.8.1 Submits supporting documents as enumerated;
12.8.2 Demands for the refund of payment of Honoraria, if unauthorized;
12.8.3 Strictly abides by Sections 288 and 289 of GAAM Volume 1, and
pertinent provisions of the General Appropriations Act, on the grant
and payment of Honoraria.

We have recommended that in order to establish an accurate and reliable balances of all municipal properties recorded in the books, management should undertake the following measures:

The Municipal Engineer and the Property Custodian conduct a yearly physical count of local road network projects and consequently update the local road map of the LGU;
The Municipal Engineer provide the Municipal Accountant and the Property Custodian the description and cost segregation of road components of various road infrastructure projects;
The Municipal Accountant keeps and maintain subsidiary ledger for roads and its components and reconcile the same to the result of the physical at the end of each year.

In view of the above noted observation, we have recommended that management:

Justify the reimbursements made by the LGU officials although the disbursement process was not substantially complied and there was an ample time for the processing of the payment of the supplier;
Henceforth, refrain from using reimbursement as method of payment for procurement unless there are unforeseen events which will justify the immediate payment thereof.

We have recommended that: 

The Municipal Accountant justify the payment of the transactions despite the absence of the BAC Resolution recommending the mode of procurement to be used and for the award of the contract;
The concerned Department Heads should justify the use of unsigned RFQ;
The Municipal Mayor justify entering into contract without the participation and recommendation of the majority of the BAC; and 
The management identifies the method of procurement used and justifies the non-conduct of competitive public bidding.

We have recommended that management justify the noted lapses and that the Municipal Mayor instruct the following concerned personnel:

The Municipal Budget officer to submit supplemental investment plan/ NADAI or additional appropriation ordinance as justification for the utilization of CY 2015 Share from Burley Tobacco Excise Tax;
The Municipal Treasurer thru the help of the Local Sanggunian to open a special account solely for the receipt and utilization of the Share from Tobacco Excise Tax. Upon creation of which, the Municipal Accountant should maintain special account under the General Fund;
Henceforth, the concerned head of the unimplemented projects evaluate the viability of the implementation of the project. Develop a time line thru which the project shall be implemented; and
Management submits liquidation documents for the tobacco seedlings distributed to farmer beneficiaries.

We have recommended the following

The Municipal Mayor creates a GFPS Execom, TWG and Secretariat that will supervise, advocate and install a GAD Focal Point System (GFPS) as well as the required Gender  Responsive Monitoring and Evaluation (M&E) System;
The Municipal Mayor with the help of the Sangguniang Bayan, formulate and adapt a Local GAD Code; 
The MSWDO being the leading authority in identifying gender related issues and concerns, see to it that GAD activities are identified through the use of HGDG and GAD Database, that the GAD plan are regularly updated and that the identified projects do address the GAD issues and concern in the long run;
The Municipal Mayor instruct the MSWDO to work closely/ coordinate with the Municipal Accountant and Budget officer to determine with certainty all GAD related activities as well as to be able to generate a detailed and credible GAD Accomplishment Report;
Henceforth, management should follow the prescribed format of GAD Accomplishment Report and see to it that said plan and budget are approved by the DILG and the PPDO; and
Also, the concerned personnel should familiarized/ update themselves with the recent promulgations regarding Gender and Development.

We have recommended that in order to establish an accurate and reliable balances of all municipal properties recorded in the books, management should undertake the following measures:
The Municipal Engineer and the Property Custodian conduct a yearly physical count of local road network projects and consequently update the local road map of the LGU;
The Municipal Engineer provide the Municipal Accountant and the Property Custodian the description and cost segregation of road components of various road infrastructure projects;
The Municipal Accountant keeps and maintain subsidiary ledger for roads and its components and reconcile the same to the result of the physical at the end of each year.

We have recommended to management that the following remedial measures be made:
The certified true copy of the official receipt as well as certificate of registration for the second-hand vehicles be submitted. Also, the technical study and other supporting documents be submitted the soonest possible time’ if any. Else the transaction will be suspended/disallowed in audit;
The BAC justifies the lack of post-qualification process;
The Municipal Treasurer and Accountant make representation to the supplier of second hand units to issue valid official receipts;
Justify the release of full payment despite absence of warranty securities posted by the supplier.  If still applicable, secure warranty security from the supplier; and
Henceforth, the BAC see to it that the proper procurement procedures be observed. The Municipal Accountant and Treasurer ensure that all supporting documents are valid before payment to the supplier is made.

We have recommended the following courses of action to be undertaken by management:

That the Budget officer and Accountant to justify the non-maintenance of the required registries, failure to duly accomplish the required obligation request; 
That the Budget Officer to coordinate with the Accountant in the preparation and submission of the supporting schedule for the SCBAA the soonest possible time so as to allow the audit team to have ample time to verify the same;
The Municipal Mayor instructs the Budget Officer and different department heads to strictly adhere to the budgetary and disbursement process; and 
Henceforth, familiarize themselves and ensure strict compliance with the different budgetary requirements.

We have recommended the following:

For the procured construction materials, the Municipal Engineer submits proof that said items were really delivered by the suppliers. In the event that said items were really delivered by the suppliers, the whereabouts as well as the status of the said items should be reported and presented for audit;
Any items which could no longer be used due to improper storage thereof should be refunded by the officials following the basic rule that accountable officers  found negligent shall be liable for loss of government funds or property as provided under Section 105(2) of Presidential Decree No. 1445;
For the utilization of the lump-sum appropriation, the Municipal Budget Officer, Accountant and Treasurer submit justification as to the reason for allowing the disbursements despite absence of re-alignment or additional appropriation ordinance;
For the unimplemented projects, the Municipal Engineer should consult the duly prepared Annual Procurement Plan (APP) for infrastructure projects, if any, since said report include the timeline for the implementation  of the project. Justification as to the reason for the non-implementation should also be submitted; and 
Lastly, we have recommended that management revisit DILG-DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2011-1, as amended, on the expenditure items covered and prohibited to be paid out of the 20% Development Fund for guidance.

We have recommended that the Management:

Justify the non-creation of LDRRM Office, non-hiring of the required staff, non-provision for the procurement of disaster preparedness equipment, non-conduct of vulnerability and adaptation assessment as well as the discrepancy in the status of the unexpended/unobligated balance of the LDRRMF in the previous years; 
Provide the liquidation documents for the received in-kind goods and locally procured goods amounting to ₱119,765.00;  
Submit realignment of funds or SB authorization for the items procured not in conformity with the LDRRMFIP;
Improve the internal control system of the LGU in order to ensure that the PPAs charged to the fund are for LDRRM related activities; 
See to it that unexpended/ unobligated funds from prior years LDRRM are treated as Trust Liability at the end of the year and duly transferred to a special trust fund account;
Utilize the prior years’ trust liability for the acquisition of disaster preparedness equipment as well as immediate assistance and services to calamity stricken constituents; and
Henceforth, provide in the Notes to Financial Statements all the required disclosures as mandated under COA Circular No. 2014-002.

We reiterated to the Municipal Accountant and Treasurer our previous years audit recommendations as follows:

Make representation with the concerned national government agencies with regards to the discrepancies noted in their records as against the books of the LGU and adjust accordingly;
Likewise, exert effort in locating the documents in support to the Due to Other GOCCs and Due to Other NGAs Account;
Henceforth, conduct periodic reconciliation of balances.

